Kubernetes, also known as K8s, is an open-source container orchestration platform used to automate the deployment, scaling, management, and monitoring of containerized applications.

Kubernetes architecture mainly consists of two parts:

Control Plane (Master Node)
Worker Nodes

The Control Plane manages the entire Kubernetes cluster.

It contains important components such as:

• API Server
The API Server is the entry point of Kubernetes. All commands and requests go through it.

• ETCD
ETCD is a key-value database that stores cluster configuration and state information.

• Scheduler
The Scheduler decides on which worker node a pod should run based on available resources.

• Controller Manager
It continuously monitors the cluster and ensures the desired state is maintained.

Now coming to Worker Nodes.

Worker Nodes are the machines where actual application containers run.

Each worker node contains:

• Kubelet
The Kubelet communicates with the control plane and manages pods on the node.

• Container Runtime
Such as Docker or Containerd, which runs containers.

• Kube Proxy
It manages networking and communication between services and pods.

Now let’s understand some important Kubernetes objects.

• Pod
The smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes that contains one or more containers.

• Deployment
Used to manage application replicas and rolling updates.

• Service
Provides stable networking and load balancing for pods.

• Namespace
Used for logical separation of resources inside the cluster.